The '''Samoan island thrush''' ('''''Turdus samoensis''''') is a species of [[passerine]] bird in the thrush family [[Turdidae]]. It is [[Endemism|endemic]] to the [[Samoan Islands]], which includes [[Samoa]] and [[American Samoa]]. It was formerly considered a subspecies of the island thrush, but in 2024 the island thrush [[species complex|complex]] was split into 17 different species by the [[IOC World Bird List|IOC]] and [[Clements checklist]] based on morphological and [[Phylogenetics|phylogenic]] differences.<ref>{{cite web |title=2024 Taxonomy Update—COMING SOON |url=https://ebird.org/news/2024-taxonomy-update |website=eBird |access-date=20 October 2024}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Proposed Splits/Lumps |url=https://www.worldbirdnames.org/new/updates/proposed-splits/ |website=IOC World Bird List v14.2 |access-date=20 October 2024}}</ref>

== Taxonomy ==
The Samoan island thrush was first described by [[clergyman]] and zoological collector [[Henry Baker Tristram]] in 1879 as ''Turdus samoensis''.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Tristram |first1=Henry Baker |title=TURDUS SAMOENSIS, ''sp. nov.'' |journal=Ibis |date=1879 |volume=3 |issue=10 |page=188 |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/8609352#page/226/mode/1up |access-date=20 October 2024}}</ref> For a long time afterwards it was considered a subspecies of island thrush. However following a phylogenetic study in 2023, and with consideration to morphological differences between subspecies, the Samoan island thrush is now treated as a distinct species.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Reeve |first1=Andrew Hart |last2=Gower |first2=Graham |last3=Pujolar |first3=José Martín |last4=Smith |first4=Brian Tilston |title=Population genomics of the island thrush elucidates one of earth's great archipelagic radiations |journal=Evolution Letters |date=January 2023 |volume=7 |issue=1 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/370065160_Population_genomics_of_the_island_thrush_elucidates_one_of_earth's_great_archipelagic_radiations |access-date=20 October 2024}}</ref> The species is [[Monotypic taxon|monotypic]]: no subspecies are recognised.<ref name=ioc>{{cite web| editor1-last=Gill | editor1-first=Frank | editor1-link=Frank Gill (ornithologist) | editor2-last=Donsker | editor2-first=David | editor3-last=Rasmussen | editor3-first=Pamela | editor3-link=Pamela C. Rasmussen | date=August 2024 | title=Thrushes | work=IOC World Bird List Version 14.2 | url=http://www.worldbirdnames.org/bow/thrushes/ | publisher=International Ornithologists' Union | access-date=26 September 2024 }}</ref>

